#### Quick Build
You can make a demon hunter quickly by following these suggestions. First, put your highest ability score in Strength or Dexterity, depending on whether you want to focus on melee weapons or finesse weapons, with your next-highest score should be Charisma. Second, choose the Criminal or Outlander background.

#### Optional Rule: Multiclassing
If your group uses the optional rule on multiclassing in the *Player's Handbook*, here's what you need to know if you choose demon hunter as one of your classes.

***Ability Score Minimum.*** As a multiclass character, you must have at least a Dexterity and Charisma score of 13 to take a level in this class, or to take a level in another class if you are already a demon hunter.

***Proficiencies Gained.*** If demon hunter isn't your initial class, here are the proficiencies you gain when you take your first level as a demon hunter: light armor, simple weapons, and martial weapons.

***Multiclassing with Warlock.*** If your demon hunter bears the Mark of Havoc and also has warlock levels, add one-third of your demon hunter levels (rounded down) to your warlock level and consult the warlock class table for total spell slots, cantrips known, and spell slot level.

\columnbreak

## Class Features
As a demon hunter, you gain the following class features.

#### Hit Points
___
- **Hit Dice:** 1d8 per demon hunter level
- **Hit Points at 1st Level:** 8 + your Constitution modifier
- **Hit Points at Higher Levels:** 1d8 (or 5) + your Constitution modifier per demon hunter level after 1st

#### Proficiencies
___
- **Armor:** Light armor
- **Weapons:** Simple weapons, martial weapons
- **Tools:** None
___
- **Saving Throws:** Dexterity, Charisma
- **Skills:** Choose two from Acrobatics, Arcana, Insight, Inti&shy;midation, Investigation, Perception, Stealth, and Survival

#### Equipment
You start with the following equipment, in addition to the equipment granted by your background:
- **(a)** two warglaives or **(b)** any martial melee weapon
- **(a)** four darts or **(b)** any simple weapon
- an explorer's pack and a memento of someone or something that was taken from you

<div class='footnote'>PART 1 | CLASSES</div>

\pagebreakNum

### Unarmored Defense
*1st-level demon hunter feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

While you are wearing no armor and not wielding a shield, your AC equals 10 + your Dexterity modifier + your Charisma modifier.

### Illidari Initiation
*1st-level demon hunter feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You have gone through the harrowing process of initiation into the Illidari, having slain a demon, consumed its flesh, and bound its soul to your own. 

As part of the process, your eyes are removed and your skin is inscribed with glowing arcane tattoos to help keep the demonic power inside you in check, though your body is mutated, giving you one or more mutations from the Demonic Mutations table. 

Additionally, you gain the following traits: 
- You have advantage on Wisdom (Survival) checks to track fiends and demons, as well as on Intelligence checks to recall information about such creatures.
- You can speak, read, and write Eredun. 
- You appear as both humanoid and fiend (demon) to any effect that detects fiends or demons, but are not affected by those that adversely affect those creature types, like *magic circle* or *dispel evil and good*.
- You cannot be possessed by a fiend or demon.

#### Fel
You can tap into a deep wellspring of chaotic energy within yourself. This wellspring is represented by fel points, which allow you to create a variety of magical effects.

You have 1 fel point, and you gain more as you reach higher levels, as shown in the Fel Points column of the Demon Hunter table. You can never have more fel points than shown on the table for your level. Your fel point total returns to full when you finish a short or long rest.

The number of fel points you have can reach negative numbers, representing you pushing beyond the limits of safety in exchange for power. When you use a fel point ability that pushes your fel point total below 0, roll a d4 and add your current fel point total to the roll. 

If the result is 0 or below, you take an amount of necrotic damage equal to your demon hunter level. This damage can’t be reduced in any way.

Some class features require your target to make a saving throw to resist the feature's effects. The saving throw DC is calculated as follows:

<div style="text-align: Center">

**Fel save DC** = 8 + your proficiency bonus + <br> your Charisma modifier

</div>

\columnbreak

##### Demonic Mutations
d12|Mutation
---|-------
1 |Your skin has turned an unnatural shade, such as red, green, dark purple, or pitch black.
2 |Your blood glows green, showing through your skin.
3 |Your skin has grown thick colored scales.
4 |You have grown horns, either short and stubby or long, curled, and jagged.
5 |Your voice echoes slightly, as if several people are speaking at once.
6 |Your nails turn hard and black, becoming like claws.
7 |Your canine teeth grow long and jagged, turning into fangs or tusks.
8 |You grow a long spaded tail. It is non-prehensile.
9 |Your feet turn into cloven hooves.
10|Your skin sprouts small spikes or spines.
11|Your eye sockets burn with a green flame that can be seen even when obscured by cloth or leather.
12|You have some other, nonfunctional mutation, as approved by the GM.

### Chaos Blades
*1st-level demon hunter feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You can use fel points to infuse your weapons with the raw power of chaos. As a bonus action, you can spend 1 fel point to imbue one weapon you're holding, enhancing it until you finish a short or long rest. 

While the weapon is imbued, attacks you make with it are magical and deal an additional 1d4 chaos damage. See the Chaos Damage sidebar for more details.

The amount of extra damage dealt increases as you level: 1d6 at 5th level, 1d8 at 11th level, and 1d10 at 17th level. Other creatures can’t gain the benefit of your chaos blades.

> #### Chaos Damage
> A number of demon hunter features refer to chaos damage. Chaos damage is a mix of raw chaotic energies that can result in several potential damage types. 
>
> Whenever you deal chaos damage, roll a number of d8s equal to the number of chaos damage dice and select one, consulting the Chaos Damage table to determine the damage type. 
>
> For example, if an effect deals 2d6 chaos damage and you roll two d8s resulting in 1 and 6, then you deal 2d6 points of either acid or poison damage.
>
> ##### Chaos Damage
> d8 | Damage Type    |d8 | Damage Type
> ---|----------------|---|------------
> 1  | Acid           | 5 | Lightning
> 2  | Cold           | 6 | Poison
> 3  | Fire           | 7 | Psychic
> 4  | Force          | 8 | Thunder

<img src='https://www.gmbinder.com/images/MhnBMAQ.png' style='position:absolute; bottom:-60px; left:45px; width:350px' />

<div class='footnote'>PART 1 | CLASSES</div>

\pagebreakNum

### Spectral Sight
*1st-level demon hunter feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You have ritually blinded your eyes, you eye sockets infused with magic, giving you a new sight that pierces through darkness and magic. You gain the following benefits:
- You are immune to the blinded condition.
- You can see normally in normal and magic darkness within 60 feet.
- You can cast *detect magic* at will by spending 1 fel point.
- You have advantage on checks and saves to see through illusions. You automatically succeed when they are cast on or by demons.
- You perceive the true form of a demonic shapechanger or a demon that is transformed by magic.

When you reach 9th level, you can focus your vision to pierce through matter as well as magic. You can spend 2 fel points to see into and through solid matter within 30 feet. To you, solid objects within range appear transparent and don't prevent light from passing through them.

This x-ray vision can penetrate 1 foot of stone, 1 inch of common metal, or up to 3 feet of wood or dirt. Thicker substances block the vision, as does a thin sheet of lead.

### Invocations
*2nd-level demon hunter feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You can draw upon dark secrets and the power of souls through magical abilities known as invocations. 

You gain two invocations of your choice. When you gain certain demon hunter levels, you gain additional invocations of your choice, as shown in the Invocations Known column of the Demon Hunter table. A level prerequisite refers to your level in this class.

Additionally, when you gain a level in this class, you can choose one of the invocations you know and replace it with another invocation that you could learn at that level.

### Fighting Style
*2nd-level demon hunter feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You adopt a particular style of fighting as your specialty. Choose one of the following options. You can't take a Fighting Style option more than once, even if you later get to choose again.

#### Dueling
When you are wielding a melee weapon in one hand and no other weapons, you gain a +2 bonus to damage rolls with that weapon.

#### Great Weapon Fighting
When you roll a 1 or 2 on a damage die for an attack you make with a melee weapon that you are wielding with two hands, you can reroll the die and must use the new roll, even if the new roll is a 1 or a 2. The weapon must have the two-handed or versatile property for you to use this benefit.

#### Profane Warrior
You learn two cantrips of your choice from the warlock spell list. They count as death knight spells for you, and Charisma is your spellcasting ability for them. Whenever you gain a level in this class, you can replace one of these cantrips with another cantrip from the warlock spell list.

\columnbreak

#### Two-Weapon Fighting
When you engage in two-weapon fighting, you can add your ability modifier to the damage of the second attack.

> #### Optional Class Features
> See Tasha's Cauldron of Everything, Pg. 41 for additional Fighting Styles. The Blind Fighting, Superior Technique, and Unarmed Fighting styles are appropriate choices for this class.

### Demonic Mark
*3rd-level demon hunter feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You choose a mark that shapes the nature of your demonically infused body. Choose the Mark of Havoc, the Mark of Vengeance, or the Mark of Wrath, all detailed at the end of the class description. 

Your choice grants you features at 3rd level and again at 6th, 10th, 15th, and 18th level.

### Ability Score Improvement
*4th-level demon hunter feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

When you reach 4th level, and again at 8th, 12th, 16th, and 19th level, you can increase one ability score of your choice by 2, or you can increase two ability scores of your choice by 1. As normal, you can't increase an ability score above 20 using this feature.

### Extra Attack
*5th-level demon hunter feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You can attack twice, instead of once, whenever you take the Attack action on your turn.

### Evasion
*7th-level demon hunter feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

Your keen instincts lets you dodge out of the way of certain area effects, such as a red dragon's fiery breath or an *ice storm* spell. When you are subjected to an an effect that allows you to make a Dexterity saving throw to take only half damage, you instead take no damage if you succeed on the save, and only half damage if you fail.

### Metamorphosis
*11th-level demon hunter feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You can let the demon bound within you take control. On your turn, you can as a bonus action let your bound demon morph your body with demonic features for 1 minute. While in Metamorphosis, you gain the following benefits.
- Your creature type becomes fiend.
- You gain a number of temporary hit points equal to your demon hunter level plus your Charisma modifier. These temporary hit points only last while you are in this form.
- Your weapon attacks are infused by Chaos Blades if they weren't already. This enhancement only lasts until the end of your metamorphosis.
- Whenever you would roll a die of Chaos Damage, you roll an additional one.

Once you use this feature, you can't do so again until you finish a short or long rest, unless you spend 3 fel points to use it again.

<div class='footnote'>PART 1 | CLASSES</div>

\pagebreakNum

### Empowered Wards
*13th-level demon hunter feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

Your arcane tattoos help protect you from harm. Whenever you make an Strength, Dexterity, or Constitution saving throw, you may add your Charisma modifier to the check (minimum of +1). 

Additionally, whenever you are forced to make a saving throw by a fiend or demon, you make it with advantage. 

### Revealing Gaze
*14th-level demon hunter feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You can concentrate fel into your charred eyes to reveal the truth of the world around you. You have blindsight to a range of 30 feet and you can spend 3 fel points to gain the benefits of the *true seeing* spell for 1 minute.

### Immortal Soul
*17th-level demon hunter feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

Your body and soul are both corrupted and protected by fel energy, granting you the following traits:
- You are considered both a humanoid and fiend (demon). You can be affected by anything that would affect either of those creature types. 
- You do not suffer from the frailty of age, can't be aged magically, and will not die of old age. You no longer need food or water.
- You cannot be charmed or frightened.
- You have advantage on saves versus any effect that exclusively affects fiends or demons.

### Prepared
*20th-level demon hunter feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

Your supernatural senses allow you to act at a moments notice. You can take two turns during the first round of any combat. You take your first turn on initiative count 30 and your second turn at your rolled initiative.

Furthermore, you can transform into and out of Metamorphosis at will as a bonus action. You only gain temporary hit points the first time you transform after a short or long rest, unless you spend 2 fel points.

<div class='footnote'>PART 1 | CLASSES</div>

